# density distribution of Estimated Project Cost
plot(density.default(x = log(data$estprojectcost)))

This plot looks at the distribution of the variable estprojectcost (Estimated Project Cost). I looked at a simple density plot and determined that there is a left-skewed distribution correlation. I had to log scale the variable because this varible looks at the costs of different building projects, so there were a few very large outlier cost values. The log scale focusses in on the main portion of the distribution. The distribution is most-likely left-skewed because of these large project-cost price ranges. My next step would be to look at what variables are causing these high project costs the most.

# omit missing values
data <- data %>% drop_na(issueddate_mth)

# desnity distribution of Issue Date Month
plot(density.default(x = data$issueddate_mth))

For this distribution, I started by taking out the missing values. I didn’t estimate the months by imputing values because I wanted to only look at the actual values that I know to be true for this density distribution plot of Issue Date Month. I found that there is a cyclic relationship which is to be expected because this distribution looks at the 12 different months. My next step would probably be to plot a time series of different varaibles compared to the months.

# filter dataset
library(dplyr)
data2 <- data %>% 
  drop_na(issueddate_yr) %>% 
  filter(workclassmapped == "New", numberstories < 3, const_type == "V  B")

First, I started by filtering the dataset into a new dataset titled data2. This funciton includes filtering the dataset to only include the “New” construciton work class, a construction type of “V B”, and buildings that have less than 3 stories. Additionally, I dropped the missing values. Again, I didn’t impute the issueddate_yr column by estimating the NAs. I didn’t do this because when I tried to fill in the NA values with the values of the nearest neighbors using a KNN imputation through the preProcess function in the caret package, there were too many missing values in the neighboring variables. This KNN imputation wasn’t accurate enough to implement on the issueddate_yr varible, so I took out the NAs as a whole.

# Permit Issue Year vs. Estimated Project Cost
p1 <- ggplot(data2, aes(x = issueddate_yr, y = log(estprojectcost), group = issueddate_yr)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  theme_bw() + 
  labs(x = "Permit Issue Year", y = "Estimated Project Cost")

# change name of variable `issueddate_yr` to `Year`
data2$Year <- data2$issueddate_yr

# Permit Issue Month vs. Estimated Project Cost
p2 <- ggplot(data2, aes(x = issueddate_mth, y = log(estprojectcost), colour = Year, group = Year)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  theme_bw() + 
  labs(x = "Permit Issue Month", y = "Estimated Project Cost")

# arrange plots onto same graph
grid.arrange(p1, p2)

The top graph plots the relationship between Permit Issue Year and the Estimated Project Cost. Overall, the project costs seem to increase over time but I also noticed a somewhat cyclic relationship.

Since I noticed this, I decided to look at the Permit Issue Month varible compared to the Estimated Project Cost varible becuase I thought it would be a better representation of why some years seem to have higher costs than others. What I determined is that there was also a cyclic relationship between the month the permit was issued and the cost of the project. This might have a lot to do with different months being more expensive to build/request a permit. It seems to be that the “more comfortable” seasons are more expensive to build in. The 5th month (May) and the 10th month (October) are both in the comfortable weather seasons of spring & fall and seem to have the highest project costs. Since these weather temperatures and conditions are more confortable for workers, prices might be more escalated. In this model, I also included a key that shows the different years onto the plot with different colors. The lighter blue dots correspond to the most recent years while the darker blue dots correspond to the earlier years in the dataset, as you can see in this key/legend.

I plotted the two graphs on top of each other in order to get a closer look at how well both the issueddate_yr and issueddate_mth variables relate to Estimated Project Cost. Overall, after looking at these adjacent boxplots of the two plots, I have concluded that the Estimated Project Cost seems to slowly increment as time goes by. There are many other variables that contribute to project costs, so my next step would be to look at a forward and backward stepwise regression analysis in order to find which variables affect Estimated Project Cost the most and plot differnt models that include them.
